english:
  title: Memorial on Bestowing a Posthumous Title and Temple Name to the Late King
  author: Choe Bu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant respectfully examines that when the Duke of Zhou established the method of posthumous names, he gathered the consensus of all under Heaven and revered the ruler and father through the Way of Heaven. The posthumous name, you see, is the trace of one's conduct. Once a name is changed, it cannot be altered for a hundred generations. How then can we take lightly the matter of bestowing a posthumous name upon our ruler and father?

    Our late King graced this world for twenty-six years, during which his sacred virtue and divine transformation were abundantly received by the people's hearts. Though it be said that as a humane sovereign he stopped at Benevolence, surely there is no dissent. To bestow the posthumous name of Benevolence is indeed to accord with reality—this is not merely the private judgment of your humble servants, but the public consensus of the entire nation.

    Now, those who debate the posthumous name should widely consult the ancient texts, broadly gather the opinions of many, carefully consider and investigate, and strive to accord with the actual virtue. Yet they cling to their narrow views, violate the public consensus, and make it their purpose to prevail over others, forcing associations and interpretations together. While they may produce eloquent arguments, how does this accord with the duty of subjects to praise their ruler and father?

    Those who argue now invoke the method of posthumous names to explain the character "Sung" (Accomplished), saying: "To be grave and magnanimous, steadfast and firm—these are the substance of Benevolence. To bring peace to the people and establish governance—these are the functions of Benevolence. For the people to flourish and ministers to prosper—these are the results of Benevolence." Your humble servants say that the method of posthumous names cannot encompass multiple meanings in a single character. The character for "Learning diligently and questioning well" cannot also carry the meaning of "ordering heaven and earth." The character for "Strength and righteousness" cannot also carry the meaning of "quelling chaos and establishing order." How then can "Accomplished" encompass these various meanings?

    Their claim that these are the substance, function, and result of Benevolence is utterly without evidence. Is this not mere fabrication? They argue that "Accomplished" means gathering all virtues together, as in Confucius's "gathering of the great accomplishment." Your humble servants say that "gathering the great accomplishment" means assembling the small accomplishments of many tones into one great accomplishment. Without the characters "gathering" and "great," "accomplished" would merely be one note in music—how could it be said to gather all virtues?

    They argue that Benevolence is merely one of the Four Virtues. Your humble servants say that Benevolence is the heart by which Heaven and Earth generate all things. In the Four Virtues, it is the source and encompasses Flourishing and Advantage and Firmness. In the Four Seasons, it is Spring and encompasses Summer, Autumn, and Winter. In humanity, it is Benevolence and encompasses Propriety, Righteousness, and Wisdom. Therefore, Master Zhu said: "Propriety is the refinement of Benevolence, Righteousness is the regulation of Benevolence, and Wisdom is the discrimination of Benevolence." How then can Benevolence be called merely one of the Four Virtues?

    They argue: "To honor the worthy and love one's kin is called Benevolence." This refers to but one aspect of Benevolence—how can it be compared with "Accomplished"? Your humble servants examining the method of posthumous names find: "To practice Benevolence and embody Righteousness is called Benevolent." This encompasses all Four Virtues comprehensively, with broad meanings. Yet they abandon this and argue instead that Benevolence falls short of "Accomplished"—why is this?

    They argue: "Our nation, in utmost sincerity, serves the great empire and never presumes. Yet regarding temple names, we alone would violate the emperor's posthumous name—can this be right?" Your humble servants say: Since generations are endless while posthumous names are limited, Zhou had King Wen, yet the feudal states had Lu Wen, Jin Wen, Wei Wen, and Cai Wen. There was King Wu, yet Lu Wu, Jin Wu, Wei Wu, and Cai Wu existed. There was King Cheng, yet Lu Cheng, Jin Cheng, Wei Cheng, and Cai Cheng existed. Even the names Kang, Zhao, Mu, and Xuan were not avoided. Lu, Jin, Wei, and Cai, being of the same clan as Zhou and dwelling in the central lands under one ruler's laws, did not hesitate to share the Son of Heaven's posthumous names—how much less should our nation? Moreover, the father of the Great Ming's High Emperor was called Ren-zu, yet the Hongxi temple name was called Ren-zong, and the imperial court itself did not avoid the ancestors' titles—how much less should our nation?

    They argue: "The founder of a state is called Taizu; he who succeeds Taizu is called Taizong—this is the universal custom of all ages, not a private designation." Your humble servants say: From the Han and Tang dynasties onward, the founder is sometimes called Taizu and sometimes Gaozu, while the successor, if possessed of merit and virtue, is called Taizong; if lacking merit and virtue, he cannot be called Taizong. If their argument were true, then the Hui Emperor of Han and the Hui Emperor of Jin should both be called Taizong, yet neither received this title. Can this be called the universal custom of all ages?

    Now, as Your Highness has just assumed the succession, the responsibility for supporting the throne rests entirely upon the great ministers. Yet when facing great matters of state, they resort to forced arguments, deceive with pretense, and stubbornly refuse to yield. Is this truly the Way of a great minister? Your humble servants, holding office in the duty of remonstrance and deliberation, cannot refrain from debate. We dare present this memorial and humbly beseech Your Highness to consider and accept it. We are overwhelmed with urgent and desperate concern.
